# User Story / Spec / Task Workflow

## 1. Purpose

This rule prevents:

- Premature implementation language inside User Stories (story should stay product-readable).
- Premature architectural commitment inside Specs (Spec is the **first** artifact where architecture lands; commitment must be minimal and traceable).
- Gold-plated or ceremonial Tasks (Tasks are optional; the default is to implement a Spec directly without Task files).
- Skipping levels (Scope Slice → Task without User Story or Spec).

It applies to any agent turn that:

- reads a Scope Slice for the purpose of writing User Stories;
- reads a User Story for the purpose of writing a Spec;
- reads a Spec for the purpose of writing Tasks or implementing the Spec;
- evaluates whether any of these artifacts is ready for the next stage.

It is the **sibling rule** of `.cursor/core/rules/feature-area-workflow.mdc`. Both rules govern the full chain `PRD → Feature Area → Scope Slice → User Story → Spec → Task`. Decisions about the post-Slice levels are defined in `docs/product-decisions/PD-001-post-slice-workflow.md`. The per-FA gate authorizing the start of User Story / Spec / Task / code work on a Feature Area is defined in `docs/product-decisions/PD-006-per-fa-delivery-readiness-gate.md` — pre-flight for every command in this rule must verify the grandparent Feature Area is at `delivery-ready` before any User Story / Spec / Task is created.

---

## 2. Required Read Order

Before any User Story / Spec / Task work, read in this order:

1. `docs/prd/state.md` — version, direction, last major change
2. `docs/prd/PRD.md` — active product definition
3. `docs/prd/questions/open-questions.md` — unresolved blockers
4. All files in `docs/product-decisions/` — durable product decisions; **PD-001 is mandatory** because it defines this workflow
5. Parent chain artifacts:
   - For `/user-story`: parent Scope Slice + grandparent Feature Area
   - For `/spec`: parent User Story + Scope Slice + Feature Area
   - For `/task`: parent Spec + User Story + Scope Slice + Feature Area
6. Sibling artifacts at the same level under the same parent (for awareness of duplication or contradiction)

Do not read steps 3–6 as optional. Open blockers, prior decisions, and sibling artifacts constrain all downstream work.

---

## 3. Terminology

Use the same hierarchy as `.cursor/core/rules/feature-area-workflow.mdc` §3. This rule scopes the bottom three layers:

```
Product
  → Feature Area
    → Scope Slice
      → User Story        (this rule)
        → Spec            (this rule)
          → Task          (this rule)
```

### User Story

A behavioral statement of one user-visible capability for one acceptance dimension of a Scope Slice. Written as "As an X, I do Y, so that Z." with 2–5 inline Acceptance Criteria in Given/When/Then form.

A User Story must:

- map to **exactly one** acceptance dimension of the parent Slice (success, error class, or edge state — see PD-001);
- stay product-readable (no routes, schemas, frameworks, status codes);
- cover a non-empty subset of the parent Slice's UX States;
- be testable via observable behavior, not via code-level assertions.

### Spec (Implementation Spec)

An engineer-readable description of how the system implements one User Story. **Spec is the first artifact in the chain where stack, schema, framework, routes, and runtime decisions may appear.**

A Spec must:

- trace every parent AC to a satisfaction strategy (here or deferred to a sibling Spec);
- carry a **mandatory Tests section** with non-empty entries per applicable layer;
- carry a **mandatory `## Async / Event / Webhook / Cron / Stream` section** (per SP-15 and PD-007) with all six sub-questions answered and a classification line on one of four canonical options — default-REST-sync must be explicitly chosen, never inferred;
- name observability signals tied to production questions;
- not include behavior outside the parent User Story's Out of Scope, UX States Covered, or ACs.

### Task

An optional implementer-readable description of one coherent commit or short PR carved out of a Spec.

A Task must:

- exist only when subdivision of the parent Spec is justified per PD-001;
- be sized for one commit / short PR;
- enumerate changes with specificity;
- list tests traceable to the parent Spec's test plan;
- carry reproducible verification steps.

**Default expectation: most Specs do not require Tasks.** Implement the Spec directly when subdivision is not justified.

---

## 4. Forbidden Actions

The following are strictly forbidden at each layer:

**At User Story stage:**

- Creating User Story markdown under `docs/product/user-stories/` **except** via `/user-story scaffold` after user approval of a `/user-story propose` proposal, or by ordinary human/manual use of `.cursor/core/templates/product/user-story.template.md`.
- Creating User Story markdown when the grandparent Feature Area is **not** at `delivery-ready` (per PD-006 — parent Scope Slice `ready-for-user-stories` is necessary but **not sufficient**).
- Editing User Story body content **except** via `/user-story scaffold` (initial population from approved proposal), `/user-story refine` (allowed product-level sections only), `/user-story promote` (narrow ready-for-spec transition only), or ordinary human/manual edits.
- Writing Specs or Tasks while the User Story has not reached `ready-for-spec`.
- Writing implementation language (routes, schemas, frameworks, HTTP status codes) inside Acceptance Criteria or any User Story body section.
- Bundling success + error + edge dimensions into one User Story.

**At Spec stage:**

- Creating Spec markdown under `docs/product/specs/` **except** via `/spec scaffold` after user approval of a `/spec propose` proposal, or by ordinary human/manual use of `.cursor/core/templates/product/spec.template.md`.
- Editing Spec body content **except** via `/spec scaffold` (initial population), `/spec refine` (product + implementation sections), `/spec promote` (narrow ready-for-implementation transition only), or ordinary human/manual edits.
- Promoting a Spec without a non-empty Tests section across applicable layers.
- **Promoting a Spec without an explicit `## Async / Event / Webhook / Cron / Stream` classification per SP-15** (default-REST-sync is a choice that must be stated, not an inferred default). Governed by PD-007.
- Committing to a stack or framework choice that is not required to satisfy the parent ACs.
- Implementing behavior outside the parent User Story's Out of Scope, UX States Covered, or ACs.
- Writing application code from within `/spec` modes — Spec is a description, not an implementation artifact.

**At Task stage:**

- Creating Task markdown under `docs/product/tasks/` **except** via `/task scaffold` after user approval of a `/task propose` proposal with `Subdivision needed: yes`, or by ordinary human/manual use of `.cursor/core/templates/product/task.template.md`.
- Editing Task body content **except** via `/task scaffold` (initial population), `/task refine` (implementation sections), `/task promote` (narrow ready-for-merge transition only), or ordinary human/manual edits.
- Creating Tasks when the proposal returned `Subdivision needed: no`.
- Tasks that exceed one commit / short PR.
- Writing application code from within `/task` modes — Tasks describe planned changes, not the changes themselves.

**At all stages:**

- Task slicing directly from `docs/prd/PRD.md`, Feature Areas, or Scope Slices (use User Story → Spec → Task chain).
- Skipping levels (Scope Slice → Spec, User Story → Task, Spec → code without acknowledging absence of Task subdivision).
- Proceeding past a known blocker without explicit user approval.
- Operating any `/user-story`, `/spec`, or `/task` mode without PD-001 present — the workflow has no governance without it.

---

## 5. Readiness Gates

### User Story lifecycle

- New User Story files default to `exploratory` after `/user-story scaffold`.
- Product-level sections not completed at scaffold are filled via `/user-story refine`.
- `/user-story promote` applies the narrow **ready-for-spec** transition only after US-01–US-12 and CC-01–CC-05 from `.cursor/core/checkers/scope-readiness-checker.md` Parts 4 + 7 are **CLEAR**.
- Spec authoring may only begin after a User Story is marked `ready-for-spec`.

### Spec lifecycle

- New Spec files default to `exploratory` after `/spec scaffold`.
- Body sections (Data Model, Contract, UI Surface, Tests, Observability, Implementation notes) are filled via `/spec refine`.
- `/spec promote` applies the narrow **ready-for-implementation** transition only after SP-01–SP-15 and CC-01–CC-05 from `.cursor/core/checkers/scope-readiness-checker.md` Parts 5 + 7 are **CLEAR** (SP-15 forces explicit Async / Event / Webhook / Cron / Stream classification per PD-007).
- Task subdivision (if needed) or direct implementation may only begin after a Spec is marked `ready-for-implementation`.

### Task lifecycle

- Task files exist only when `/task propose` returned `Subdivision needed: yes` and the user approved.
- New Task files default to `exploratory` after `/task scaffold`.
- Body sections (Changes, Tests, Verification Steps) are filled via `/task refine`.
- `/task promote` applies the narrow **ready-for-merge** transition only after TK-01–TK-09 and CC-01–CC-05 from `.cursor/core/checkers/scope-readiness-checker.md` Parts 6 + 7 are **CLEAR**.

### Scope Slice → User Story gate

A Scope Slice may produce User Stories only when **both** of the following hold:

1. The Scope Slice's status is `ready-for-user-stories` (set via `/feature-area promote-slice` after **CLEAR** of SS-01–SS-10 + CC-01–CC-05, or manual equivalent).
2. The grandparent Feature Area's status is `delivery-ready` (set via `/feature-area clear-for-vertical` after **CLEAR** of DR-01–DR-05 + CC-01–CC-05, or manual equivalent).

This double gate authorizes per-FA parallel delivery: a `delivery-ready` Feature Area can run its User Story / Spec / code chain in parallel with macro elaboration of other Feature Areas. Governed by `docs/product-decisions/PD-006-per-fa-delivery-readiness-gate.md`.

Pre-flight for `/user-story propose` and `/user-story scaffold` must verify both conditions and stop with a clear error if either is unmet. The same pre-flight applies transitively to `/spec propose`, `/spec scaffold`, `/task propose`, and `/task scaffold` via their parent chain — a Spec or Task cannot exist before its ancestor Feature Area is `delivery-ready`.

### User Story → Spec gate

A User Story may produce a Spec only when its status is `ready-for-spec` (set via `/user-story promote`).

### Spec → Task or Implementation gate

A Spec may produce Tasks only when its status is `ready-for-implementation` (set via `/spec promote`). Direct implementation without Tasks is also allowed only after this status.

### Task → Merge gate

A Task may be implemented and merged only when its status is `ready-for-merge` (set via `/task promote`).

---

## 6. Decomposition Rules

### User Story decomposition

For each `ready-for-user-stories` Scope Slice:

1. Identify distinct acceptance dimensions in the Slice's UX States + Included Behavior + Acceptance-Level Outcome.
2. Draft one User Story per dimension. Rule of thumb: 3–6 stories per Slice.
3. Each story carries 2–5 inline Acceptance Criteria in Given/When/Then form.
4. Each story's UX States Covered references state names exactly as they appear in the parent Slice.
5. Cross-check every story against PRD Hard v0 exclusions and the parent Slice's Excluded Behavior.

### Spec decomposition

Default: **one Spec per User Story.** Multiple Specs only when distinct technical surfaces (e.g. backend job + frontend screen + shared schema) cannot land in one coherent implementation; the reason must be stated explicitly in the Spec proposal.

### Task decomposition

Default: **no Tasks.** Implement the Spec directly. Create Tasks only when ALL of the following hold:

- The Spec touches multiple distinct technical surfaces.
- Those surfaces cannot land in one coherent commit / short PR.
- Each surface can be implemented and verified independently.
- The team needs separate PR cadence per surface.

### v0 boundary enforcement

Apply the same v0 exclusion list as `.cursor/core/rules/feature-area-workflow.mdc` §6 to every User Story, Spec, and Task. A story / spec / task that touches a deferred surface must be marked `deferred` with a reference to the PRD exclusion.

---

## 7. Blocker Rules

### When NEED_HUMAN=true is required

Set `NEED_HUMAN=true` when any of the following exist:

- An open question in `docs/prd/questions/open-questions.md` directly blocks this artifact.
- A product or architectural decision required by this artifact is undecided.
- A boundary in an AC, Spec contract, or Task scope cannot be drawn without a business rule not yet stated.
- For a Spec: a non-trivial trade-off (consistency vs availability, sync vs async, etc.) lacks an explicit choice.
- Two valid interpretations of the parent artifact produce meaningfully different artifacts at this level.

Do not proceed past `NEED_HUMAN=true` without explicit user approval.

`NEED_HUMAN` propagation (CC-04): a child artifact with `NEED_HUMAN=true` must have its parent artifact also carrying `NEED_HUMAN=true` until resolved.

### When NEED_UPDATE=true is required

Set `NEED_UPDATE=true` when any of the following exist:

- This rule (`.cursor/core/rules/user-story-workflow.mdc`) does not cover the current situation.
- A template in `.cursor/core/templates/product/` is missing or incomplete for the current artifact.
- The checker in `.cursor/core/checkers/scope-readiness-checker.md` cannot evaluate the current artifact.
- PD-001 does not address a load-bearing situation; consider a follow-up PD that supersedes or extends PD-001.

Do not silently work around a gap. Surface it.

---

## 8. Artifact Locations

| Artifact | Location | Template |
|---|---|---|
| User Story | `docs/product/user-stories/<fa-kebab>--<slice-kebab>--US-<NNN>--<short-kebab>.md` | `.cursor/core/templates/product/user-story.template.md` |
| Spec | `docs/product/specs/<fa-kebab>--<slice-kebab>--US-<NNN>--<short-kebab>.spec.md` | `.cursor/core/templates/product/spec.template.md` |
| Task | `docs/product/tasks/<fa-kebab>--<slice-kebab>--US-<NNN>--T-<MMM>--<short-kebab>.task.md` | `.cursor/core/templates/product/task.template.md` |

`<NNN>` and `<MMM>` are three-digit zero-padded sequence numbers within their parent. When multiple Specs exist per User Story, append `--A`, `--B`, etc. before the `.spec.md` extension.

---

## 9. Anti-Patterns

Never:

- Write ACs as test cases (`assert(...)`, `expect(...)`).
- Reference a route, endpoint, schema, or component class in a User Story body.
- Promote a Spec with an empty Tests section.
- Promote a Spec that introduces architecture that does not trace to a parent AC.
- Promote a Task without reproducible Verification Steps.
- Scaffold Tasks when the proposal returned `Subdivision needed: no`.
- Operate any `/user-story`, `/spec`, or `/task` mode without PD-001 in `docs/product-decisions/`.
- Use "Feature Group" language in User Story / Spec / Task narratives — that legacy term is reserved to PRD section citations only (see `.cursor/core/rules/feature-area-workflow.mdc` §3).
- Use "story card", "ticket", "issue" interchangeably with "User Story"; use "design doc", "RFC" interchangeably with "Spec".
- Mark any artifact as `ready-*` while it has unresolved `NEED_HUMAN` flags.
- Treat "Spec looks done enough" as authorization to skip the checker.
